{
  "texts": [
    "Then since M, y ⊩ □ γ ¬p, yR γ u implies M, u ⊩ ¬p, which with xR β u implies M, x ⊮ □ β p. Thus, □ β p → □ δ ♢ γ p is valid over F.In the other direction for the empty α case, suppose F does not satisfy (6.10), so ∀x∀y(xR δ y → ∀u(yR γ u → ¬xR β u)).",
    "(6.12)Define M exactly as we did after (6.11).",
    "Then by the same form of argument used to show that M, z ⊩ □ β z in the proof from (6.11), one can show that M, x ⊩ □ β p from (6.12).",
    "Moreover, the exact same argument used to show M, x ⊮ □ δ ♢ γ p above works here.",
    "Thus, □ β p → □ δ ♢ γ p is not valid over F.Finally, for the claim about local correspondence, where ∀x ψ(x) is (6.9), we claim that ∀x ⊑x 0 ∀x ψ(x) is a local correspondent of ♢ α □ β p → □ δ ♢ γ p. If there is a model M based on F and an x 0 ∈ M such that M, x 0 ⊮ ♢ α □ β p → □ δ ♢ γ p, then there is an x ⊑ x 0 such that M, x ⊩ ♢ α □ β p but M, x ⊮ □ δ ♢ γ p.Then by the same reasoning as in the first paragraph of this proof, it follows that ψ(x) is falsified by x, so ∀x ⊑ x 0 ∀x ψ(x) is falsified by x 0."
  ]
}